[ ] decide whether the formatter should own horizontal (intra-line) spacing $ Investigating core-seam's save_file delegation (2026-07-03) surfaced that the topiary formatting.scm query only governs vertical spacing/indentation; horizontal gaps around !priority, +tags, and other single-line metadata sigils are silently stripped to zero on any write that reformats the line, since topiary drops unlisted inter-token whitespace by default. Adding @prepend_space per missing field (or one unified field-role rule) does add spacing, but produces INCONSISTENT results depending on node adjacency: name->first-field and context/predecessor->id come out double-spaced, while priority/completed_date->id come out correctly single-spaced. Root cause not yet isolated -- looks tied to how topiary reconciles a directive-forced space against whitespace already present in the text it re-parses (serialize_actions_canonical already emits correctly-spaced raw text before topiary's pass), but the exact rule governing when that produces 1 vs 2 spaces is still unknown. Open question underneath the bug: should the formatter own horizontal spacing at all, given formatting.md v2.1.0 deliberately scoped it OUT (whitespace-insensitive by design, spacing left to lint-only enforcement)? Or was that scoping itself the mistake, given topiary's actual default is to strip absent whitespace rather than pass it through untouched as the spec assumed? Needs real research into topiary's extras/whitespace model before deciding, not more trial-and-error. See also platform trust charter's round-trip property test action -- same underlying bug class (2026-07-02 multi-tag data loss). $!2#019f28c7-c3e8-7ee2-87e4-ba8cd020da43
